\section{\texttt{gmean}: geometric mean}

\subsection{Use}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=lstchapelf,numbers=none]
proc gmean(
   ref x: [] real                  // the array being averaged
) : real where x.rank == 1 {
\end{lstlisting}


\subsection{Theory}

Given a sequence $(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n)$ of \emph{strictly positive
  real numbers}, the geometric mean is
\begin{align}
  \tilde{x} &= \left[\prod_{i=1}^n x_i \right]^{1/n}\label{eq:gmean-prod}
\end{align}
For large $n$ and small individual values of $x_i$, however,
(\ref{eq:gmean-prod}) can lead to underflow. It is much more robust to
write
\begin{align}
  \tilde{x} &= \exp\left\{ \ln \left[ \left(\prod_{i=1}^n x_i
      \right)^{1/n}\right]\right\}\nonumber \\
    &= \exp\left[\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \ln(x_i)\right].\label{eq:gmean-explog}
\end{align}

\section{\texttt{gmom}: geometric-modulus mean}

\subsection{Use}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=lstchapelf,numbers=none]
proc gmom(
   ref x: [] real                  // the array being averaged
) : real where x.rank == 1 {
\end{lstlisting}


\subsection{Theory}

\texttt{gmom} is my own humble attempt to generalize the idea of a
geometric mean to sequences containing negative and null values, as well as
positive.

First, consider a sequence $(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n)$ containing only
negative values. It is reasonable to define its ``geometric'' mean as
\begin{align}
  \tilde{x} &= -\exp\left[\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \ln(\left|x_i\right|)\right].\label{eq:gmean-neg}
\end{align}
For a sequence containing negative, null, and positive values,
$\ln(\cdot)$ can no longer be used, and the singularity at the origin
needs to be avoided. A function that has those attributes and is
asymptotically equal to $\ln(\cdot)$ for large positive values of its
argument is the \emph{log-modulus} function introduced by
\cite{john1980alternative}:
\begin{equation}
\logmod(x) \equiv \sign(x)\ln(|x| + 1).\label{eq:def-logmod}
\end{equation}
Note that, asymptotically,
\begin{equation}
  \logmod(x) \sim \begin{cases}
    x, & x \sim 0, \\
    \sign(x)\ln(|x|), & x \gg 1,
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}
and that $\logmod(x)$ is odd.

In order to mimic (\ref{eq:gmean-explog}), we need the inverse of $\logmod$:
\begin{align*}
  y &= \sign(x)\ln(|x| + 1),  \\
  \sign(y)y &= \ln(|x| + 1),  \\
  \intertext{(because $L$ is odd)}
  \exp\left(\sign(y)y\right) &= |x| + 1, \\
  \exp\left(|y|\right) &= |x| + 1, \\
  |x| &= \exp\left(|y|\right) - 1, \\
  x &= \sign(y)\left[ \exp\left(|y|\right) - 1\right],
\end{align*}
whence
\begin{equation}
\expmod(x) \equiv \sign(x)\left[ \exp\left(|x|\right) - 1\right]\label{eq:def-expmod}
\end{equation}
is the \emph{exponential-modulus} function.

We are now ready to define the \emph{geometric-modulus} mean:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{x} \equiv \expmod\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n
  \logmod(x_i)\right].
\label{eq:def-gmom}
\end{equation}
Evidently, for a sequence of positive real values where $x_i \gg 1\;
\forall i = 1, \ldots, n$, (\ref{eq:def-gmom}) will produce results
which are very close to (\ref{eq:gmean-explog}). However, if on the
other hand $x_i \ll 1\; \forall i = 1, \ldots, n$, (\ref{eq:def-gmom})
will be very much like the arithmetic mean, which is undesirable. The
solution to always obtain a ``geometric mean''-like behavior for any
sequence (now including possibly null and negative values as well) is
to re-scale before averaging, by means of the following sequence of
operations:
\begin{align}
  \delta &= \frac{\min(|x_i|)}{16}, \qquad x_i \ne 0, \label{eq:delta}\\
  \xi_i &= \frac{x_i}{\delta}, \label{eq:xi}\\
  \tilde{\xi} &= \expmod\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n
    \logmod(\xi_i)\right], \label{eq:tilde-xi}\\
  \tilde{x} &= \delta \tilde{\xi}.\label{eq:tilde-x}
\end{align}
The factor 16 in (\ref{eq:delta}) is arbitrary and is meant to force
all non-null $\xi$ to be ``sufficiently'' far from $\pm 1$.


\section{\texttt{steep}: Steepest descent method for nonlinear least squares}

The description here is quite detailed and long, and may in the future
be moved to a proper place. It is heavily based on
\cite{gavin2022levenberg} and code listings in Matlab cited therein.

Consider then a set of $m$ ``observed'' data points $\vet{y} = (y_1, \ldots,
y_m)$ possibly observed at the independent variable values $\vet{x} = (x_1, \ldots,
x_m)$.. A model may be proposed to approximate or estimate these
points, of the type
\begin{equation}
  \vet{\hat{y}} = \vet{f}(\vet{x},\vet{p})
\end{equation}
where $\vet{p} = (p_1, \ldots, p_n)$ are $n$ parameters that we want
to find to get $\vet{\hat{y}}$ as ``close'' as possible to $\vet{y}$.

An ``squared error'' covariance matrix can be defined as follows:
\begin{equation}
\met{V}_{m\times m} \equiv \left( \mat{\vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}}_{m
  \times 1}\mat{\vet{\hat{y}} - \vet{y}}^\tr_{1 \times m}\right)
\end{equation}
A ``weight'' matrix is now the inverse of $\met{V}$:
\begin{equation}
\met{W} \equiv \met{V}^{-1},
\end{equation}
but it is not clear to me if this is the ``right'' way to introduce
$\vet{W}$, since it is a rather roundabout way to define the next
element, which is the objective function that we wish to maximize,
namely
\begin{equation}
\chi^2(\vet{p}) \equiv \mat{\vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}}^{\tr}_{1
  \times m}\met{W}_{m \times m}\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}}_{m \times 1}\label{eq:chi2-matrix}
\end{equation}
\cite{gavin2022levenberg} mentions that $\met{W}$ is often a diagonal
matrix (which makes a lot of sense, and may the only case implemented
in the routine; let's see):
\begin{equation}
W_{ij} = \frac{\delta_{ij}}{\sigma_{y_{(i)}}^2}.
\end{equation}

We translate (\ref{eq:chi2-matrix}) to indicial notation:
\begin{equation}
\chi^2(p_k) = [\hat{y}_i(p_k) - y_i ]W_{ij}[\hat{y}_j(p_k)-y_j];
\end{equation}
then,
\begin{align}
  \parder{\chi^2}{p_k} &= [\hat{y}_i(p_k)- y_i]W_{ij}\left[\parder{\hat{y}_j}{p_k}\right] +
                          \left[\parder{\hat{y}_i}{p_k}\right]W_{ij}[\hat{y}_j(p_k)-y_j] \\
                       &= [\hat{y}_i(p_k)-y_i]W_{ij}\left[\parder{\hat{y}_j}{p_k}\right] +
                               [\hat{y}_i(p_k)-y_i] W_{ji}\left[\parder{\hat{y}_j}{p_k}\right]\\
                               \intertext{which, since $\met{W}$ is symmetric, yields}
                       &= 2 [\hat{y}_i(p_k)-y_i]W_{ij}\left[\parder{\hat{y}_j}{p_k}\right]                              
\end{align}
or
\begin{equation}
\met{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2}^\tr_{1\times n} =  2 \mat{ \met{\hat{y}}-\vet{y} }^\tr_{1\times m} \met{W}_{m\times m} \met{J}_{m\times n}
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
J_{jk} = \parder{\hat{y}_j}{p_k}
\end{equation}
are the elements of the jacobian matrix
\begin{equation}
  \met{J}_{m \times n} =
  \begin{bmatrix}
    \parder{y_1}{p_1} & \parder{y_1}{p_2} & \cdots & \parder{y_1}{p_n} \\
    \parder{y_2}{p_1} & \parder{y_2}{p_2} & \cdots & \parder{y_2}{p_n} \\
    \vdots            &                   & \ddots & \vdots \\
    \parder{y_m}{p_1} & \parder{y_m}{p_2} & \cdots & \parder{y_m}{p_n} \\
  \end{bmatrix}.
\end{equation}
The gradient of $\chi^2$ is
\begin{equation}
  \mat{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2}_{n\times 1} = 2\met{J}^\tr_{n\times m}\met{W}_{m\times m} \mat{ \vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y} }_{m\times 1},
\end{equation}
because $\met{W}^\tr = \met{W}$.

We start at an initial guess $\vet{p}$ and systematically calculate
\begin{align*}
  \mat{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2} &= 2\met{J}^\tr\met{W} \mat{\vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}},\\
   \mat{\vet{h}} &= t \mat{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2}\\
   \mat{\vet{p}} &\leftarrow \mat{\vet{p}} - \mat{\vet{h}}
\end{align*}
until a stopping criterion is reached such as
\[
\left | \vet{h}\right| < \epsilon.
\]
Note the minus sign in the update of $\vet{p}$, because we are reaching for a
minimum of $\chi^2$.  The problem of course lies in what value of $t$ to
use. In some simple examples, it can be fixed at some small number.
A better option (we shall see) is \emph{backtracing
line search}, which consists of changing the algorithm to 
\begin{align*}
  \mat{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2} &= 2\met{J}^\tr\met{W} \mat{\vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}},\\
    t &\leftarrow 1\\
    \text{while} \;\chi^2(\vet{p} - t\vet{\nabla}\chi^2) &> \chi^2(\vet{p}) - \frac{t}{2}\left|\vet{\nabla}\chi^2\right|^2 \;\text{do}
       \;t \leftarrow \beta t\\
    \vet{h} &= t \mat{\vet{\nabla}\chi^2} \\
    \vet{p} &\leftarrow   \vet{p} - \vet{h}
\end{align*}
where $\beta=0.1$ (hardwired and constant) is the bactracing parameter, until 
\[
\left | \vet{h}\right| < \epsilon.
\]
The stop criterion $\epsilon$ has a default value of $1.0\times 10^{-6}$,
and is chosen by the user by setting the variable \texttt{epsilon}.
The Jacobian matrix is calculated
with centered finite
differences.


\section{\texttt{gnewton}: Gauss-Newton method for nonlinear least squares}

Two consecutive estimates of $\vet{\hat{y}}$ are related (to first order) by
\begin{equation}
  \met{\hat{y}(\vet{p} - \vet{h})}_{m\times 1} =
  \met{\hat{y}(\vet{p})}_{m\times 1} - \met{J}_{m\times n}\met{h}_{n\times 1}.
\end{equation}

Consider two consecutive evaluations of $\chi^2(\vet{p})$:
\begin{align}
  \chi^2(\vet{p}) &= \Big[\met{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big]^\tr\met{W}
                    \Big[\met{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big], \\
                    \chi^2(\vet{p}-\vet{h}) &=
                    \Big[\met{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{J}\met{h} - \met{y}\Big]^\tr\met{W}
                    \Big[\met{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{J}\met{h} - \met{y}\Big].
\end{align}
As always, indicial notation is quicker and more clear:
\begin{align}
  \hat{y}_i(p_l-h_l) &= \hat{y}_i(p_l) - J_{ik}h_k,\\
  \chi^2(p_l) &= \left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) - y_i\right]W_{ij}\left[ \hat{y}_j(p_l) - y_j\right],\\
  \chi^2(p_l-h_l) &= \left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) - J_{ik}h_k - y_i\right]W_{ij}\left[ \hat{y}_j(p_l) -J_{ik}h_k - y_j\right].\label{eq:chi2-lin}
\end{align}
Differentiating  (\ref{eq:chi2-lin}) with respect to $h_k$,
\begin{align}
  \parder{\chi^2}{h_k} &= \left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) - J_{ik}h_k - y_i\right]W_{ij}\left[ -J_{ik}\right]+
  \left[ - J_{ik}\right]W_{ij}\left[ \hat{y}_j(p_l) -J_{ik}h_k - y_j\right]\nonumber\\
  &= \left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) - J_{ik}h_k - y_i\right]W_{ij}\left[ -J_{ik}\right]+
  \left[ - J_{jk}\right]W_{ji}\left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) -J_{jk}h_k - y_i\right]\nonumber\\
  &= -2\left[ \hat{y}_i(p_l) - J_{ik}h_k - y_i\right]W_{ij}J_{ik}
\end{align}
which translates in matrix form to
\begin{equation}
  \Bigmat{\parder{\chi^2}{h_k}}_{1\times n} =
  -2 \Big[\mat{\hat{y}(\vet{p})}_{m\times 1} - \met{J}_{m\times n}\met{h}_{n\times 1} - \met{y}_{m\times 1}\Big]^\tr_{1\times m}
  \met{W}_{m\times m}\met{J}_{m \times n}.
\end{equation}
But
\begin{equation}
\vet{\nabla}_h\chi^2 = \parder{\chi^2}{h_k}\vet{e}_k,
\end{equation}
whence
\begin{equation}
  \Bigmat{\vet{\nabla}_h\chi^2} =
  -2 \met{J}^\tr \met{W}
  \Big[\mat{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{J}\met{h} - \met{y}\Big]
\end{equation}
At an extremum, $\vet{\nabla}_h\chi^2 = \boldn{0}$, so that
\begin{align}
  -2 \met{J}^\tr \met{W}
  \Big[\mat{\hat{y}(\vet{p})} - \met{J}\met{h} - \met{y}\Big] &= \mat{\boldn{0}},\nonumber\\
  \met{J}^\tr \met{W}\met{J}\met{h} -
  \met{J}^\tr \met{W}\Big[\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big] &= \mat{\boldn{0}}\nonumber\\
    \met{J}^\tr \met{W}\met{J}\met{h} &= 
  \met{J}^\tr \met{W}\Big[\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big].\label{eq:newton-h}
\end{align}
The Newton method now consists of starting at some value of $\vet{p}$,
iterating the solution $\vet{h}$ of (\ref{eq:newton-h}), and setting
\[
\met{p} \leftarrow \met{p} - \met{h}
\]
until, again, 
\[
\left | \vet{h}\right| < \epsilon.
\]

\section{\texttt{levmar}: Levenberg-Marquardt}

The Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm is a combination of the steppest
descent and Newton methods. First, note that the update
$\mat{\vet{h}}$ of the steepest descent method can be written in the
form
\begin{align}
  \mat{\vet{h}} &= 2t\met{J}^\tr\met{W} \mat{ \vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}
  },\nonumber\\
  \lambda \mat{\vet{h}} &= \met{J}^\tr\met{W} \mat{ \vet{\hat{y}}-\vet{y}}
\end{align}
with $\lambda = 1/(2t)$, while the update $\mat{\vet{h}}$ of the
Newton method is given by (\ref{eq:newton-h}). Combining both, we
first have
\begin{equation}
\Big[\met{J}^\tr \met{W}\met{J} + \lambda \met{I}\Big]\met{h} = 
\met{J}^\tr \met{W}\Big[\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big],
\end{equation}
where $\met{I}$ is the identity matrix. This was further modified by
\cite{marquardt--algotithm} and \cite{fletcher1971modified} by setting
\begin{equation}
D_{ij} = J_{ki}W_{kl}J_{lj}\delta_{(ij)}
\end{equation}
--- that is, $\met{D}$ is a diagonal matrix formed from the diagonal
elemens of    $\met{J}^\tr \met{W}\met{J}$ .  In our implementation,
$\lambda = 1$ as a starting value. We now solve for the
update $\met{h}$ and calculate $\rho$ in each iteration as 
\begin{align}
\Big[\met{J}^\tr \met{W}\met{J} + \lambda \met{D}\Big]\met{h} &= 
\met{J}^\tr \met{W}\Big[\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big],
\\
\rho &= \frac{\chi^2(\vet{p}) - \chi^2(\vet{p}-\vet{h})}
{ \left| \met{h}^\tr \lambda \met{D}\met{h} + \met{J}^\tr \met{W}\Big[\mat{\vet{\hat{y}}(\vet{p})} - \met{y}\Big]\right|}
\end{align}
Now if $\rho > \epsilon_r = 1\times 10^{-3}$, then
\begin{align*}
  \met{p} &\leftarrow \met{p} - \met{h}, \\
  \lambda &\leftarrow \lambda/\beta{\mathord{\downarrow}}
\end{align*}
otherwise,
\begin{equation*}
\lambda \leftarrow \beta{\mathord{\uparrow}} \lambda
\end{equation*}
where $\beta{\mathord{\downarrow}} = 5$ and
$\beta{\mathord{\uparrow}} = 2$ implement the \emph{delayed
gratification approach}. Note that $\beta$ is reminiscent of, but not
the same as, the backtracing parameter $t$ of the steepest descent
method.







